Rating: 4
Onion soup recipes do not vary that much -- butter, onions, beef and/or chicken stock and herbs. The trick is getting the onions right. If you get them right, your soup will be great. Sometimes my onions turn out and sometimes they don't. So I enjoyed reading everyone's tips on caramelizing the onions, and think I now have it down. I doubled the recipe so it gave me a chance to compare pans. I used a cast iron frying pan and a le creuset enameled cast iron french oven. I started out with medium heat and added a pinch of sugar and a pinch of salt, and then turned them down a bit after they started to brown. The onions in the cast iron pan caramelized quicker at first, but then the onions in the le creuset pan caught up with them at about 40 minutes. I deglazed a couple times and I think that helped. In total I had them caramelized in about 50 minutes. Once the onions were caramelized in both pans, I combined them in the le creuset. I used a touch more beef than chicken stock and added bay leaf, thyme and a splash of balsamic vinegar as others suggested. I finished with Gruyere cheese. I make extra and freeze portions in plastic bags for quick meals. Thanks for all the tips. I think I will try the versions with meat and shitake mushrooms.

