Rating: 4
I like this recipe, its chief contribution all that sweet garlic! But I would peel it, then softly mash it, to avoid the fusile oils. Often, we make too much of the caramelization routine. For 40 years, I have used Julia Childs' method, with the addition of a little salt and sugar at the high end of a mere half-hour saute in olive oil. The oven method seems to me excessive, and I wonder if those poor rural French who long ago concocted this dish would have had the time, laborers as they were. Apart from that, it is simple. If we make this dish too complicated, we'll enjoy it less often. By all means, do some excellent brandy, just a quarter cup or so, but add it to the end of the sugar and salt saute, and dry it up so as to create a little smoky taste. French onion soup, of course, always tastes best the next day. But who can wait? So make it in large quantity to savour today, and to revel in tomorrow. And it can't hurt to go to a really stinky cheese for the gratinee. I have even used Maytag Blue! Be creative! For the bread, find a nice whole wheat baguette. Just a final thought, if you want, put a mere teaspoon of the leftover brandy into each bowl for the browning of the cheese, and you'll get some nice burning. I am an old guy, and I assure you my method really works for a fine stinky dish.

